00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.110
Good day, I'm Norman Wildberger, and today we're&nbsp;
going to talk about Leonard Euler and pentagonal&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:13.110 --> 00:00:21.030
numbers. Euler was the greatest mathematician of&nbsp;
the modern age. Originally Swiss, he spent a lot&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:21.030 --> 00:00:29.760
of his life in Germany and in Russia, in St.&nbsp;
Petersburg. He lived in the time 1707 to 1783,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:29.760 --> 00:00:37.110
during which he contributed to almost all branches&nbsp;
of mathematics and established foundational&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:37.110 --> 00:00:43.380
notation, many important theorems, and in fact,&nbsp;
discovered entire new branches of mathematics.

00:00:43.380 --> 00:00:52.710
Today we're going to look at how he interpreted&nbsp;
the pentagonal numbers that we talked about in the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:52.710 --> 00:01:00.390
previous video and connected them in a remarkable&nbsp;
way with number theory. So I remind you that the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:00.390 --> 00:01:07.350
pentagonal numbers are the sequence here, and by&nbsp;
looking at the table of differences for these,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:07.350 --> 00:01:13.110
we were able to extend these pentagonal&nbsp;
numbers also to sort of negative values.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:13.110 --> 00:01:22.530
The formula for the pentagonal numbers was n&nbsp;
times (3n - 1) over 2, and last time I posed&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:22.530 --> 00:01:28.920
the question of whether these numbers over&nbsp;
here, sort of fictitious pentagonal numbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:29.730 --> 00:01:36.720
play an important role. Euler showed&nbsp;
that they did. He considered putting&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:36.720 --> 00:01:43.590
the proper pentagonal numbers together with&nbsp;
these other ones into a single sequence,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:43.590 --> 00:01:50.160
and he observed that the differences formed&nbsp;
by this sequence were rather irregular and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:50.160 --> 00:01:56.520
did not have an easily understood pattern.&nbsp;
Even back then, in the 18th century, Euler&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:56.520 --> 00:02:03.420
was aware of the importance of looking at a table&nbsp;
of differences. What I've done here is I've just&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:03.420 --> 00:02:09.180
circled in green the proper pentagonal numbers&nbsp;
that actually come from geometrical figures.

00:02:11.120 --> 00:02:16.700
Now let's take a little diversion to a little bit&nbsp;
of elementary number theory, and I would explain&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:16.700 --> 00:02:23.000
to you an important function of a natural number&nbsp;
called Sigma(n), which is the sum of the divisors&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:32.690
of n. So a divisor of a natural number like 6&nbsp;
is another natural number that divides it. Six&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:32.690 --> 00:02:41.600
has divisors 1, 2, 3, and 6 itself, and Sigma of&nbsp;
6 is defined to be the sum of all these divisors,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:41.600 --> 00:02:51.080
which in this case is 12. Here's a table of the&nbsp;
values of the Sigma function for a natural number&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:51.080 --> 00:03:00.860
n. It's a rather interesting pattern which&nbsp;
doesn't have a clear structure. We can see&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:00.860 --> 00:03:08.090
the primes reflected by the fact that if you take&nbsp;
a prime like 7, then its Sigma will be 1 more than&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:08.090 --> 00:03:16.850
it because it only has two factors: 1 and itself.&nbsp;
Also, 6 has the rather remarkable property that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:16.850 --> 00:03:24.830
its Sigma is exactly 2 times it. That's what is&nbsp;
known since ancient times as a perfect number.

00:03:27.800 --> 00:03:33.920
Alright, so there's n, there's Sigma(n), and&nbsp;
a natural question is how could you calculate&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:33.920 --> 00:03:41.150
this? How could you extend this table without&nbsp;
actually factoring a number and counting up&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:41.150 --> 00:03:49.730
the sum of all of its divisors? Euler discovered a&nbsp;
beautiful way of doing just that. Euler discovered&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:49.730 --> 00:03:57.770
a recursive formula for the Sigma function, which&nbsp;
means that the values for any particular n can be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:57.770 --> 00:04:04.550
expressed in terms of values for smaller natural&nbsp;
numbers. Here's the relation that he found:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:05.270 --> 00:04:11.240
Sigma of capital N could be written&nbsp;
as a sum of Sigmas of smaller numbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:11.240 --> 00:04:23.210
explicitly Sigma of (n - 1) plus Sigma of (n -&nbsp;
2) minus Sigma of (n - 5) minus Sigma of (n - 7),&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:23.210 --> 00:04:30.800
and so on. What are these numbers that are&nbsp;
appearing here that we're subtracting from n? They&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:30.800 --> 00:04:35.990
are exactly the generalized pentagonal numbers in&nbsp;
the sequence we wrote down on the previous slide:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:35.990 --> 00:04:48.380
1, 2, 5, 7, 12, 15, 22, 26, and so on. There's&nbsp;
also the issue of sign—some of them are plus and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:48.380 --> 00:04:57.380
some of them are minus. Well, the rule that Euler&nbsp;
stated was that if you look at the pentagonal&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:57.380 --> 00:05:05.870
number that you're considering subtracting,&nbsp;
that's called P_n. If that n is an odd number,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:05.870 --> 00:05:12.920
then Euler says we put a plus sign in front, and&nbsp;
if n is an even number, we put a negative sign in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:12.920 --> 00:05:20.120
front. In the sum, there are only a finite number&nbsp;
of terms because we agree that the Sigma function&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:20.120 --> 00:05:27.020
is only defined for terms with positive values.&nbsp;
So once what's inside here becomes negative,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:27.020 --> 00:05:33.830
we ignore it. There's one more convention that&nbsp;
if we end up with a Sigma of 0 as the last term,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:33.830 --> 00:05:40.040
we must interpret Sigma of 0 as equaling&nbsp;
n, the number that we started with.

00:05:42.260 --> 00:05:50.660
Alright, so let's illustrate by calculating Sigma&nbsp;
of 12. So we subtract 1, so there's Sigma of 11.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:50.660 --> 00:05:58.370
We subtract 2, Sigma of 10. We subtract 5 with&nbsp;
a minus sign. We subtract 7 with a minus sign.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:58.370 --> 00:06:06.530
We subtract 12 with a plus sign. Twelve minus&nbsp;
twelve is zero, so this Sigma of 0 has to be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:06.530 --> 00:06:12.620
interpreted as the number 12. These ones here&nbsp;
we can look up in the table if we have all the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:12.620 --> 00:06:23.120
values up to 11. Sigma of 11 is 12. Sigma of 10&nbsp;
is 18. Sigma of 7 is 8. Sigma of 5 is 6. So the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:23.120 --> 00:06:28.370
formula says that Sigma of 12 is the sum of these&nbsp;
things, which is 28, and that is indeed correct.

00:06:28.370 --> 00:06:34.160
This Sigma function is, in fact, a very&nbsp;
interesting and important number theoretical&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:34.160 --> 00:06:40.640
function, and I can't resist throwing in&nbsp;
a fascinating aside discovered relatively&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:40.640 --> 00:06:46.250
recently by Professor Jeffrey Lagarias&nbsp;
from the University of Michigan in 2002.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:46.250 --> 00:06:52.130
I've mentioned the Riemann hypothesis in an&nbsp;
earlier video. I didn't tell you what it was;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:52.130 --> 00:06:59.450
it's rather complicated if you set it out in&nbsp;
the traditional way. So here is his equivalent&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:59.450 --> 00:07:05.090
formulation of the Riemann hypothesis. It's&nbsp;
essentially that this inequality is true for&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:05.090 --> 00:07:12.350
any natural number. What does it say? It says&nbsp;
that Sigma(n), the sum of the divisors of n,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:12.350 --> 00:07:23.990
is less than or equal to H_n plus log of&nbsp;
H_n times e to the H_n. What is H_n? It's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:23.990 --> 00:07:31.550
this rational number here: the sum of all the&nbsp;
fractions 1 + 1/2 + 1/3 all the way up to 1/n.

00:07:31.550 --> 00:07:41.180
Here's another discovery that Euler made, having&nbsp;
to do with pentagonal numbers. It concerns another&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:41.180 --> 00:07:48.200
function called the partition function, which&nbsp;
plays an important role in combinatorics. Alright,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:48.200 --> 00:07:52.880
so without going into a lot of detail,&nbsp;
let me just say rather quickly that P(n)&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:52.880 --> 00:07:59.930
is the number of ways to partition a natural&nbsp;
number n. By that I mean, here's an example:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:59.930 --> 00:08:08.150
P(4) is 5 because if we partition four, group&nbsp;
four into blocks, each block consisting of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:08.150 --> 00:08:14.390
a natural number, then here are the ways we&nbsp;
can do it. We can write it as 4, or as 3 + 1,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:14.390 --> 00:08:24.080
or as 2 + 2, or as 2 + 1 + 1, or as 1 +&nbsp;
1 + 1 + 1, and those are the five ways of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:24.080 --> 00:08:33.710
partitioning 4. So we say that P(4) is 5. This&nbsp;
partition function is an important function in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:33.710 --> 00:08:40.550
computer science and other things, and it's also&nbsp;
rather hard to compute. Euler discovered, again,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:40.550 --> 00:08:46.340
a remarkable recursive formula for the&nbsp;
partition function, and it turns out that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:46.340 --> 00:08:52.740
it's essentially the exact same recursive&nbsp;
formula that holds for the function Sigma.

00:08:52.740 --> 00:09:02.640
So for example, P(14)—to evaluate that, you&nbsp;
take 14 minus 1, 14 minus 2, 14 minus 5,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:02.640 --> 00:09:09.660
14 minus 7, 14 minus 12. You put plus signs&nbsp;
and minus signs in front just as we did before,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:09.660 --> 00:09:17.040
and then you evaluate these ones which you assume&nbsp;
you already know. There's what they happen to be,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:17.040 --> 00:09:23.670
and if we calculate that, we get 135,&nbsp;
telling us that the next term would&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:23.670 --> 00:09:31.770
be 135 without actually having to&nbsp;
partition 14 into all possible ways.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:31.770 --> 00:09:37.170
This becomes a much more efficient way&nbsp;
of calculating the partition function,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:37.170 --> 00:09:41.820
and it's still to this day probably one of the&nbsp;
best ways of calculating the partition function.

00:09:41.820 --> 00:09:46.890
